":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Kenedon Manor, Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England"},"en":{"1387–":"1387–Deceased","1387–Female":"1387–Deceased","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1409–1439":"1409–1439","1361–Male":"1361–Deceased","about 1409":"about 1409","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1387":"1387","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","Abt 1400":"about 1400","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1490":"1490","1439":"1439","Tavistock, Devon, England":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Kenedon Manor, Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mewye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Muse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mewies","meanings":["English:  see  Mewse   and  compare  Mewis  ."]},{"name":"Muse","meanings":["English: variant of   Mewes  .","French: nickname from Old French <i>muse</i> ‘amusement, dissipation’, denoting a dissolute person.","Somali: from a Somali Muslim personal name, from Arabic   Musa   ‘Moses’. It is also found in Ethiopia, Kenya, and Djibouti. Compare   Musse  . — Note: Since Somalis traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, this name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":68,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Mewye was born in 1387, in Tavistock, Devon, England as the daughter of Mewye. She married John Hals in 1408. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Sherford, Devon, England."},"et":{"1387–":"1387–Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1409–1439":"1409–1439","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","about 1409":"umbes 1409","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1387":"1387","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1490":"1490","1439":"1439","Tavistock, Devon, England":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Kenedon Manor, Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1387–":"1387–Kuollut","1387–Female":"1387–Kuollut","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1409–1439":"1409–1439","1361–Male":"1361–Kuollut","about 1409":"noin 1409","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1387":"1387","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","Abt 1400":"noin 1400","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1490":"1490","1439":"1439","Tavistock, Devon, England":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Kenedon Manor, Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1387–":"1387–Décédée","1387–Female":"1387–Décédée","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1400–1490":"14